    sampleAnswer: {
      en: "I'd like to describe an experience from about a year ago when I helped a classmate who was struggling significantly with a challenging statistics assignment.\n\nThe classmate was a friend named Minh, who had transferred into our programme from a different faculty and hadn't had the prerequisite mathematics background that the rest of us had. We had a major statistics project due in two weeks, worth 30% of our grade, and he was clearly overwhelmed and becoming quite distressed.\n\nI noticed he seemed stressed during a study session and asked if everything was okay. When he explained his difficulties, I suggested we work through the material together over several sessions. I redesigned my own revision approach so that I was explaining concepts to him rather than simply reviewing them myself — which, incidentally, deepened my own understanding considerably.\n\nWe spent about three evenings going through the fundamentals: probability, regression analysis, and hypothesis testing. I tried to explain things using practical examples related to his interests, which seemed to make abstract concepts more concrete. By the final session before the deadline, he had developed enough confidence to complete the assignment independently.\n\nHe ultimately received a good mark on the project. But honestly, what I remember most is how I felt during the process — there was something deeply satisfying about watching someone's confusion gradually turn to comprehension and confidence. It reinforced my belief that teaching others is actually one of the most effective ways of consolidating your own knowledge.",
